andoned city-owned buildings in the 1980s, fought to keep them for decades, and eventually began a long, complicated process to turn their illegal occupancy into legal cooperative ownership. Amy Starecheski here not only tells a little-known New York story, she also shows how property shapes our sense of ourselves as social beings and explores the ethics of homeownership and debt in post-recession America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHome ownershipxSocial aspects. 0aOccupancy (Law)xSocial aspects. 0aOccupancy (Law)zNew York (State)zNew York. 0aSquatter settlementszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aSquatterszNew York (State)zNew YorkxAttitudes. 4aLower East Side. 4aNew York City. 4adebt. 4agentrification. 4ahomeownership. 4aoral history. 4aproperty. 4asocial movements. 4asquatting. 4aurban homesteading. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226400006423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226400006.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles